^SERIES = GSE287976
!Series_title = Single-Cell Omics Analysis of Human Basophils Reveals Two Transcriptionally Distinct Populations
!Series_geo_accession = GSE287976
!Series_status = Public on Jan 07 2026
!Series_submission_date = Jan 24 2025
!Series_last_update_date = Jan 08 2026
!Series_summary = Single-omics technologies have been extensively used to study the heterogeneity of cell populations. However, human basophils are remarkably underrepresented in single-cell RNA-sequencing studies. Here, we used CITE-seq (single-cell RNA-sequencing with feature barcoding) to profile the basophil transcriptome, to detect cell surface epitopes, and to barcode specific cell populations.
!Series_overall_design = We performed CITE-seq of low-density leukocytes and isolated basophils from the peripheral blood of 4 healthy donors. For the first dataset, side scatter (SSC) low leukocytes were sorted and mixed with SSClow Lin- CCR3+ FCÎµR1+ basophils. To generate the second dataset, we sorted SSClow Lin- CCR3+ FCÎµR1+ basophils and mixed them with SSClow Lin- CCR3+ FCÎµR1+ c-KIT+ basophils. To generate the third dataset, we MACS-enriched CCR3+ cells from low density leukocytes, producing 3 datasets from 2 donors in 2 indepedent experiments. To generate the fourth dataset, we repurposed the full-length amplified cDNA material used to produce the third dataset. Specifically, we performed long-read sequencing of 2 samples (1 library from each donor) using the Oxford Nanopore Technology.
!Series_overall_design = 
